Over the past millennia, life expectancy has drastically increased. While a mere 
25 years during Bronze and Iron ages, life expectancy in many European countries 
and in Japan is currently above 80 years. Such an increase in life expectancy is 
a result of improved diet, life style, and medical care. Yet, increased life 
span and aging also represent the most important non-modifiable risk factors for 
several pathologies including cardiovascular disease, neurodegenerative 
diseases, and cancer. In recent years, neutrophils have been implicated in all 
of these pathologies. Hence, this review provides an overview of how aging 
impacts neutrophil production and function and conversely how neutrophils drive 
aging-associated pathologies. Finally, we provide a perspective on how processes 
of neutrophil-driven pathologies in the context of aging can be targeted 
therapeutically.

